mdd_notes: Had a suicide attempt last Thursday and ended up in the hospital. Had been feeling fine and then she noted she felt overwhelmed and took a lot of pills. Called a friend right away, who then took her to the hospital.
suicide_notes: Her only suicide attempt happened last week. She reported that she generally doesn't feel suicidal, but spurr of the moment decided to take too much of her medication. Once she felt the effects, she fell over. It freaked her out, so she called a friend, who then got her to the hospital. This happened last Thursday, and she reported that she was discharged yesterday (12/6/21) from the hospital. She has a follow up visit with a psychiatrist this week, and therapy starting later this month. She was also put on Lexipro and has another "emergency" medication for acute symptoms. She reported vaping to reduce her anxiety today because that latter medication made her feel very out of it.     I sent over the mental health resource page as soon as we talked during the depression section of the MINI. She was appreciative of those. I also discussed the option of having Jeremy reach out to her and checking in. For now, she feels fine without him reaching out because she has several psychiatrist appointments set up. She said she will reach out to us if she would like to talk to him. She repeated several times that this suicide attempt really surprised her. She had no previous intent or plan, but in a moment of feeling overwhelmed, she took too much of her medication with the intent to die. That feeling was very quickly gone, and so she called for help and was able to get to the hospital.     After talking with her, my impression is that she now has an abundance of resources to keep her safe. She also does not feel like she is in any current danger. I called Dr. Kendrick's office, but he was not in, so I will email him with this information and see if additional follow up is necessary. I will also contact Dr. Love and confirm whether she should be included in the study. -LCE 12/7/21    Dr. Kendrick confirmed that no further follow up is needed. -LCE 12/8/21

mdd_notes: Most severe was when she had to give up custody of her kids.   Discussed resources and provided national suicide hotline. Discussed how to get a therapist and support through reaching out to her PCP.
suicide_notes: Pt reported feeling hopeless in the last month and thinking she would be better off dead "a few times" in the past month. She reported she injured herself on purpose through taking  extra anxiety medication. She reported "I wanted everything to stop". When she took this medication she reported she did not want to die, and this was not a suicide attempt. She reported not remembering the name or amount of medication. She reported she "would never kill (herself)" but has had passive SI in the past when she "wonders" about falling asleep and not waking up. Pt reported she is currently safe and does not have any suicide ideation, plan, or intent.
mania_notes: Her most severe episode of experiencing these symptoms lasted 3 weeks and she was hospitalized in a psychiatric hospital for it. She reported experiencing these symptoms for at least a week on 3 separate occasions. She reported "I did things I never would have done in my usual state." She reported excessive spending, hypersexuality, and doing dangerous things.  She would only get one hour of sleep and feel "rested".
panic_notes: Reported she has frequently suffered from panic attacks and have gone to the hospital for them. They severely impact her functioning and she is fearful of them.
ptsd_notes: She did not want to talk about the event. Questions were asked trusting her understanding of symptoms. Pt was visibly anxious and distressed during the conversation. She agreed to answer without elaborating.
aud_notes: Reported hallucinations when cutting down on drinking. Went to the hospital and they reported it was from drinking. It occurred once.
psychdis_notes: Once she heard and saw things other people could not hear or see due to alcohol withdrawal. She was hospitalized for it. Otherwise, she has not experienced these.

suicide_notes: PF313AUD scored a 4 on the suicidality section of the MINI. She reported one suicide attempt when she was 15 years old. She got into a fight with her boyfriend and took "a bunch" of her mother's medications. She then started to feel funny, got scared, and went to her mother. They called 911 and went to the hospital. She recognized the reason she took the pills was because she didn't have anyone to talk to. She has not had any suicide attempt and has not engaged in any self-injury since. She has a history of recurring depression and anxiety. She is not currently in a depressive episode. She is seeing a psychiatrist and a psychologist regularly who she said are both great. She has protective factors of family, purpose, religion, and loving being alive. She reported having lots of resources to refer to if she were to feel worse. Additional resources were provided. The PI was called during the visit and relevant information was discussed. An email was sent to the PIs after the visit with the relevant information.

screen_psychiatric_disorder_other: Diagnosed with Borderline PD three years ago
screen_notes: Follow-Up on 5/20/20: Borderline PD Dx was by an ER physician after a suicide attempt. Suicide attempt was not due to a large life trauma event, but more so feelings of loneliness and depression over a sustained period. Attempt was made by taking pills, so a pretty atypical method of suicide for a BPD patient. Continues to suffer from depression symptoms and has a history of suicidal ideation without intent. However, 2017 was her last suicidal attempt and she has never had non-suicidal self-harm behaviors. Has seen a therapist since 2016, therapist said she had BPD behaviors, but never felt they were severe enough to warrant a diagnosis. Instead, said her therapist often appraised lots of loneliness, depression, and feelings of separation from others. Past relationships: had a separation in 2016 that did result in more typical BPD behavior (felt her world was falling apart). Had another separation earlier in 2020, but did not have nearly as severe a reaction this time around.     Per Ellen Frank, PhD, this sounds like a likely misdiagnosis from the ER physician and this person has depression with labile mood, more in line with what the person's therapist noted. Dr. Frank says it is okay to enroll this participant.

mini_notes: Suicidality is actually moderate, based on participant's "yes" response to "In the past month did you... Think about suicide?" Participant has no plans or intent, so because there is no intent, participant meets inclusion criteria.     Sent email to Dr. Kendrick regarding MINI and suicidality. 7/8/20 ~SB

mdd_notes: Lost 15 lbs over the course of 6 months during this time.   Cycled on and off for the course 10+ years and didn't really improve until this last year when she got some medication help.
mania_notes: Gets periods of high activity or the need to get lots done. She feels like she can get many things done at once in these periods, but admits they don't all get done/can't get done in that time period. Expresses that she is easily distracted by things to add to her list of to-dos at those times, and so the time can become jumbled with tasks. These periods of high activity have caused issues with spouse, especially relating to her spending. When she was younger, this manifested as periods of risky driving. Feels the need to get things done when she has energy, especially because she has a lot of chronic fatigue and pain.
panic_notes: Feelings of panic attacks tend to correlate with times where she has been drinking more. Associated with social situations and stress as well.
socanxiety_notes: Trys to avoid situations and/or feels she has to drink to endure it. Will leave a party and sit in the car for some time before being able to go back in. Has built up confidence and coping skills and can endure it for job and other situations.
aud_notes: Craving associated with uncomfortable social situations

This RA provided additional resources. Protective factors include her cat, friends, family, and enjoying mornings and biking. suicide_notes: Participant PF316AUD scored a 9 (moderate) on the suicidality section of the MINI. She endorsed feeling hopeless the past month, engaging in self-injurious behavior, and making 2 suicide attempts in her lifetime.  She reported 3 episodes of depression over the course of her life. She did meet criteria for a current depressive episode although she endorsed being in a "much better place and doing well" compared to past years. She attempted suicide via hanging 2 years ago and via cutting in December of 2021. She reported doing much better now and not having any suicidal thoughts or ideation. She reported engaging in cutting 5 times in the past month. This RA and the participant discussed coping strategies. The participant reported music helps her and the participant and RA came up with reading, watching movies, and calling her friend to add to a list of coping strategies. The participant wrote these down and reported she would put it on a bulletin board near her bed as a reminder. The participant reported she was seeing a therapist in 2019 and it was "very helpful". She said she is not seeing one now because she hasn't gotten around to looking for one and she is concerned it will cost money. This RA used motivational interviewing around going back to a therapist. The patient was very receptive and reported she would like to. The patient said she was on anti-depressant medication at one point and she said it must have "helped a lot" because things got worse when she stopped taking it. RA and participant discussed going back to a psychiatrist. The participant was in agreement that seeing a psychiatrist would help. Protective factors include her dog, friends, and family. Additionally, she always makes sure to have at least one fun event/outing planned in the future to look forward to. She reported she has insurance and will be working full time in a week or two which will help provide additional financial support for seeing a therapist.      This RA provided the participant with national and local mental health resources. The PI was called and all relevant information was discussed. An email was sent to the relevant PIs with the MINI and a summary of the situation. One of the PIs knows resources in the area and plans to reach out to the participant to provide some further assistance.

suicide_notes: HealthRhythms' participant PF317AUD scores a 20 (high) on the suicidality section of the MINI. She endorsed feeling hopeless and thinking she would be better off dead in the past month. She had thoughts about hurting herself or suicide 15 times in the past month. She described these thoughts as moderate in intensity and able to be controlled. She denies having a suicide method or plan in mind and she denies current ideation. She has recurring depression and met MINI criteria for current depression. She reported she has been having a hard time since being in a car accident a few years ago. She sees a psychologist every week and a psychiatrist every other week who are treating her and both very active in her care. She reported they have a safety plan in place where she calls close friends first, her psychologist second, and a suicide hotline last when she is in a "down" place. She has not engaged in any self-injury, has not taken any steps toward suicide, and has not had a suicide plan in mind in the past month. She has never had a suicide attempt. She reported feeling safe and she said her safety plan is very effective. She reported she has very supportive friends she can go to. Her protective factors include her friends, her pets, and walking with her dogs. She reported coping skills of hugging her dogs, meditation, deep breathing, and self-soothing. She reported she regularly engages in these activities. She had resources and reported she would not be afraid to use the suicide hotline. Additional resources were provided.      The PI of the study was called during the visit and relevant details were discussed. This summary and the MINI were sent to the PIs via email after the visit.

suicide_notes: Participant PM315AUD scored a 16 on the suicidality section of the MINI. He endorsed "occasionally" feeling hopeless, sometimes feeling like he would be better off dead, occasionally having thoughts of suicide and harming himself, and he reported one suicide attempt over 50 years ago. He has a history of depression. His depression started as a child from a "rough childhood and difficult relationships with family members". He reported one suicide attempt when he was in 10th grade when his girlfriend broke up with him. At that time, he took a sleeping medication that he reported did not have any effect and he felt "dumb" for making the attempt. He has not taken any steps toward suicide since. He reported he has had thoughts about suicide and harming himself for most of his life. He described them as "abstract". He reported they are passing and that he does not feel a desire to act on them. Additionally, he reported he "would never hurt himself, suicide is something (he) would never attempt again, and (he) is repulsed by the thought". He reported he is "in a great place in life" and is enjoying life. Protective factors include religious and moral beliefs, family, friends, enjoyment of life, and not wanting someone to find him dead. He has seen therapists for years and recently stopped seeing one because he was doing well. Resources were provided to him. The PI on the study was called during the visit and an email was sent with a summary after the visit.

mdd_notes: See full notes under suicidality section.
suicide_protective: He reported having a very lovely family that cares a lot about them. He reported he would not leave them. They tell him there is more to life and give him hope. They prevent him from acting on his suicidal thoughts. He reported he resorts to friends, video games, and YouTube when he is feeling low.
suicide_notes: Summary:  Participant reported the first time he had thoughts of hurting himself was a few years ago. He lost someone very close to him to cancer. He reported 3 suicide attempts through cutting his wrists in January 2021, January 2022, and August 2022. He reported feeling like he couldn't get "out of his troubles". He reported troubles related to career, family, relationships, and life.  He reported thoughts in the past to be very severe. He initially reported severe suicidal thoughts in the past month with intent and then later in the assessment reported he has not had them and has not felt motivated or inspired to act on them for the past six months (Report of thoughts and severity were inconsistent throughout interview. He originally reported 20 severe thoughts of suicide in the past month but, when asked later about the inconsistency, insisted that that was incorrect and RA had heard him wrong).  When RA inquired about his getting help, he reported he went to the hospital multiple times in the past month and is getting "all the help he needs" through therapists and psychiatrists. He reported feeling much better and going to the hospital has decreased his suicidal thoughts and he reported he has not had them within the past few months (after previously saying they were severe in the past month).     Safety plan:  RA provided participant with resources and participant and RA made a safety plan. Participant reported any time he has thoughts of hurting himself he will reach out to his family or therapist. RA and participant discussed coping skills. Participant reported playing video games, hanging with friends, and calling his family is helpful when he is feeling down.     Protective factors:  He reported having a very lovely family that cares a lot about him and vice versa. He reported he would not leave them. They tell him there is more to life and give him hope. They prevent him from acting on his suicidal thoughts. He reported he resorts to friends, video games, and YouTube when he is feeling low.    This MINI was sent to the PI and a copy was put into Box.
closing_notes: Based on inconsistent suicidality report participant was excluded. Baseline was not completed so RA could focus on supporting the patient, giving them resources, developing a safety plan, and MI around coping skills. SC
